Part 4: Simplex (1+x)^n vs Cuboid (1+2x)^n nesting
======================================================================

Simplex: I = (1+x)^n → I(2) = 3^n → H values: 3, 9, 27, 81, 243...
Cuboid:  I = (1+2x)^n → I(2) = 5^n → H values: 5, 25, 125, 625...

Achievable H from pure simplex/cuboid packing (H ≤ 1000):
  H =    1 = simplex^0
  H =    3 = simplex^1
  H =    5 = cuboid^1
  H =    9 = simplex^2
  H =   15 = simplex^1 × cuboid^1
  H =   25 = cuboid^2
  H =   27 = simplex^3
  H =   45 = simplex^2 × cuboid^1
  H =   75 = simplex^1 × cuboid^2
  H =   81 = simplex^4
  H =  125 = cuboid^3
  H =  135 = simplex^3 × cuboid^1
  H =  225 = simplex^2 × cuboid^2
  H =  243 = simplex^5
  H =  375 = simplex^1 × cuboid^3
  H =  405 = simplex^4 × cuboid^1
  H =  625 = cuboid^4
  H =  675 = simplex^3 × cuboid^2
  H =  729 = simplex^6

Total achievable: 19 values in [1, 1000]
Density: 0.0380 of odd integers

======================================================================
Part 5: General brick products Π(1+c_i·x) → H values
======================================================================
Algebraically, Π(1+2c_i) generates ALL odd numbers ≥ 1.
The constraint is which Ω structures actually occur in tournaments.

Key forbidden values from tournament constraints:
  H=7 = 1+2·3: needs Ω = K_3 (tesseract), impossible (HYP-1230)
  H=21 = 3·7: needs factor 7, but I(component,2)=7 impossible
       OR H=21 = 1+2·10: needs Ω = K_10 with NO disjoint pairs
       But α₁=10 forces α₂≥1 at achievable n, so H≥25

======================================================================
Part 6: Nesting simplices in cuboids — Catalan structure?
======================================================================
Substitution interpretation:
  Cuboid at y: (1+2y)
  Simplex: y = (1+x)
  Compose: (1+2(1+x)) = 3+2x
  At x=2: 3+2·2 = 7
  THIS IS THE FORBIDDEN VALUE H=7!

Nesting hierarchy (substitute y=1+cx into 1+dy):
  (1+1(1+1x)) = 2+1x              at x=2:    4  
  (1+2(1+1x)) = 3+2x              at x=2:    7  FORBIDDEN
  (1+3(1+1x)) = 4+3x              at x=2:   10  
  (1+1(1+2x)) = 2+2x              at x=2:    6  
  (1+2(1+2x)) = 3+4x              at x=2:   11  
  (1+3(1+2x)) = 4+6x              at x=2:   16  
  (1+1(1+3x)) = 2+3x              at x=2:    8  
  (1+2(1+3x)) = 3+6x              at x=2:   15  
  (1+3(1+3x)) = 4+9x              at x=2:   22  

Double nesting (z=1+e(1+c(1+dx))):
  1+1(1+1(1+1x)) at x=2: 5
  1+2(1+1(1+1x)) at x=2: 9
  1+1(1+2(1+1x)) at x=2: 8
  1+2(1+2(1+1x)) at x=2: 15

======================================================================
Part 7: H=7 = simplex-in-cuboid composition — obstruction meaning
======================================================================

The fact that (1+2(1+x)) at x=2 = 7 = forbidden H value suggests:

H=7 is forbidden BECAUSE it represents a "simplex packed inside a cuboid"
— a composition that the tournament structure cannot support.

The independence polynomial I(Ω, x) is MULTIPLICATIVE over connected
components but NOT over nesting/composition.

Tournament Ω has the property that its independent sets arise from
GEOMETRIC constraints (vertex disjointness of cycles). This geometry
prevents the "nested packing" that would produce I = 3+2x.

Similarly:
  H=21 = 3·7: a simplex (3) times a simplex-in-cuboid (7)
  The factor 7 carries the obstruction.

The (2,3) principle:
  - x=2 (OCF point): growth rate 2 = k-nacci limit
  - x=3 (cuboid point): growth rate 3 = weighted k-nacci limit
  - I(Ω, 2)/I(Ω, 1) measures "simplex-to-OCF" ratio
  - I(Ω, 3)/I(Ω, 2) measures "OCF-to-cuboid" ratio

Ratios I(3)/I(2) and I(2)/I(1) at n=5:
